sect1.para:
Bipolar and related disorders are complex, chronic conditions characterized by periods of significantly depressed and elevated mood. Individuals with bipolar disorder experience marked impairments in occupational and interpersonal functioning, and these difficulties have been shown to persist despite clinical remission in approximately half of the diagnosed population (Sanchez-Moreno et al.,
         2009
      ). Indeed, bipolar disorder ranks as the overall ninth leading cause of disability worldwide (World Health Organization, 
         2001
      ) and the sixth leading cause of disability in individuals aged 10 to 24 years worldwide (Gore et al., 
         2011
      ). Most patients with bipolar disorder will have at least one other comorbid psychiatric diagnosis, with anxiety disorders, substance use disorders
         disorders
      , personality disorders, and attention deficit hyperactivity disorders being highly prevalent (Krishnan, 
         2005
      ). The presence of comorbid psychiatric diagnoses
         diagnoses
       can contribute to poorer illness outcomes (American Psychiatric Association, 
         2013
      ; Bauer et al., 
         2005
      ), and the use of substances can intensify manic symptoms (Rowland & Marwaha, 
         2018
      ). Bipolar disorder
         Bipolar disorder
       is also associated with a higher prevalence of medical conditions, often leading to premature mortality (Chan et al., 
         2022
      ).

Bipolar disorder
   Bipolar disorder
 has a strong genetic component (Chen et al., 
   2013
), but environmental influences such as stress or trauma may impact illness onset and severity (Aldinger & Schulze, 
   2017
). Stressful life events that can contribute to bipolar disorder onset or course include childbirth, divorce, unemployment, or loss of a parent early in life (Rowland & Marwaha, 
   2018
). In addition to the connection between stressful life events and the lifetime development of bipolar disorder, 60% of individuals with bipolar disorder report at least one stressful event before a manic or depressive episode in the past 6 months, further suggesting the strong role that stress plays in the development and manifestation of bipolar disorder and related episodes (Rybakowski, 
   2021
).

sect2.para:
It is important to note that bipolar II disorder is not a milder version of bipolar I disorder. While individuals with bipolar II disorder
            bipolar II disorder
          do not experience the impairment of mania, they often experience longer and more frequent depressive episodes as compared to bipolar I, which significantly impacts functioning (American Psychiatric Association, 
            2013
         ). Indeed, the functional impairment observed in bipolar disorder has largely been attributed to the experience of depressive symptoms versus manic or hypomanic symptoms (Bauer et al., 
            2001
         ). Like bipolar I, diagnosing bipolar II requires that the hypomanic and major depressive episodes are not better attributed to schizoaffective disorder, schizophrenia, schizophreniform, disorder, delusional disorder, or other specified or unspecified schizophrenia spectrum or other psychotic disorder (American Psychiatric Association, 
            2022
         ).

The lifetime prevalence of bipolar II disorder is 0.4% (Merikangas et al.,
            2011
         ) to 1.57% (Clemente et al., 
            2015
         ). The average age of onset is during the mid-20s and is somewhat later than that observed in bipolar I disorder
            disorder
         . Bipolar II may be more prevalent in females than males (Diflorio & Jones, 
            2010
         ). Major depressive episodes typically precede hypomania in those ultimately diagnosed with bipolar II disorder (American Psychiatric Association, 
            2013
         ). If an individual initially had a diagnosis of major depressive disorder, the diagnosis would convert to bipolar II disorder upon the experience of a hypomanic episode. Similarly, a diagnosis of bipolar II disorder would convert to bipolar I if a manic episode were to occur.

The “with seasonal pattern” specifier can be applied if at least one type of episode tends to occur during a particular time of year for at least 2 years. The prototypical example of this specifier involves an onset of depression in the fall or winter that remits in the spring, although hypomania and mania may show seasonal patterns as well. The “with seasonal pattern” specifier is more common with bipolar II diagnoses compared to bipolar I (Fico et al., 
            2021
         ). The “in partial remission” specifier is utilized if symptoms of an episode still remain but no longer meet full criteria for the episode, or if there have been no significant symptoms for a period of less than 2 months. The “in full remission specifier” is employed when there have been no significant symptoms of an episode for at least 2 months. Mild, moderate, and severe specifiers can indicate the number and severity of symptoms as well as the degree of impairment for both major depressive and manic episodes, although the definitions of the severity specifiers vary slightly based on whether it is a manic or depressive episode.
